Time Series Forecasting of APPLE Stock Prices using Python¶

In this Jupyter notebook, we will be utilizing techniques from the field of time series analysis to analyze the historical stock prices of APPLE. We will be using tools from the Python ecosystem such as the yfinance library to retrieve the data and various forecasting models to make predictions about future stock prices.

We will start by importing the necessary libraries and loading the historical stock data for APPLE. Next, we will perform exploratory data analysis to gain a better understanding of the trends and patterns in the stock prices.

After that, we will use techniques of time series analysis to create a model that can predict future stock prices. This will include techniques like decomposition, stationarity testing and feature engineering.

Finally, we will use different models such as ARIMA, SARIMA, LSTM to model the time series and evaluate their performance. We will also interpret the results of these models and draw insights from them.

Overall, the goal of this notebook is to gain a deeper understanding of the stock market trends of APPLE and make informed predictions about its future performance using the techniques of time series analysis and modeling.

Time series descomposition¶

Once we have a better understanding of the data through exploratory data analysis, we can now proceed to the next step which is time series decomposition.

In [67]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Perform time series decomposition
result = seasonal_decompose(ts_, model='multiplicative',period=30)
result.plot()
plt.show()

Using the freq argument in the seasonal_decompose() function is an important step in analyzing the time series data in your Jupyter notebook. This is because the seasonal_decompose() function uses the frequency of the time series to separate the data into its trend, seasonal, and residual components. Without specifying a frequency, the function would not be able to separate the data correctly, and the results of the decomposition would be inaccurate.

By specifying the frequency as 'D' or 365 (assuming your data is daily), you ensure that the function uses the correct number of data points for each seasonal component. This allows for a more accurate decomposition of the time series, which can be useful for identifying patterns and trends in the data.

Additionally, by specifying the frequency, you can better understand the underlying patterns in the data and make more accurate predictions. For example, if you know that there is a yearly pattern in the time series, specifying a daily frequency will allow you to see this pattern more clearly.

Next, we will perform stationarity testing to check if our time series is stationary. A time series is stationary if the mean, variance and covariance are constant over time.

In [68]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

# Perform Dickey-Fuller test
dftest = adfuller(ts_)
print(f'p-value: {dftest[1]}')

p-value: 0.9321115016347086

A p-value less than 0.05 indicates that the time series is stationary. Since, our p-value is greater than that value, we need to make the time series stationary in order to be able to model it.

In [69]:
#Differencing
ts1= ts_ - ts_.shift(1)

#Test stationarity
resultp = adfuller(ts1.dropna())
print('p-value: ', resultp[1])

p-value:  3.84564048489496e-21

We can see now that our time series has become stationary. The plot of the data would look like:
